T18	p 1268 1491	Scientists, therefore, are interested in L. capsica because of its genetic proximity to destructive species in the Liberibacter family. They are focusing on how members of the family mutate to be able to live inside a host.
T19	i 1309 1319	L. capsica
T20	p 1492 1867	After zeroing in on 21 L. capsica genes known for their infectious potential, the scientists discovered a subset of mutations on genes that affect pilus. Pilus are hair-like protein structures that allow cells to attach to surfaces. The L. capsica bacteria uses the pilus to enter hosts, reside in them, and assimilate their DNA. Insects then transmit the bacteria to plants.
